        "---\n",
        "title: \"When to Use Anytime-Valid Inference\"\n",
        "description: \"A practical guide to anytime-valid inference in randomized experiments, early stopping, and decisions based on interim results.\"\n",
        "aliases:\n",
        "  - /anytime-valid-inference.html\n",
        "categories: [Inference, AB Testing]\n",
        "toc: true\n",
        "toc-title: \"On this page\"\n",
        "toc-location: left\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Decisions based on interim A/B-test results\n",
        "\n",
        "Your team has finished a new feature and wants to test it with an A/B\n",
        "test. Before launch, you choose the primary KPI, the smallest effect worth\n",
        "detecting, and a 5% false-positive rate. Given the expected traffic and\n",
        "baseline conversion rate, the power calculation implies a runtime of twenty\n",
        "days.\n",
        "\n",
        "The decision is scheduled for day twenty, but the interim results are visible\n",
        "the whole time. Whether the experimentation platform is built in-house or\n",
        "supplied by GrowthBook, Eppo, Statsig, or Optimizely, the dashboard\n",
        "recomputes the treatment estimate and p-value each morning, and anyone on the\n",
        "team can look.\n",
        "\n",
        "The p-value is 0.15 on day one and 0.08 on day two. It falls below 0.05 on day\n",
        "three and stays there through day eight. The team begins discussing whether\n",
        "to ship before the scheduled day-twenty decision.\n",
        "\n",
        "The p-value on the dashboard, however, was not calibrated for a day-three\n",
        "ship decision. Its 5% false-positive rate is a property of one prespecified\n",
        "analysis: fit the model once, on day twenty, and reject if $p \\leq 0.05$.\n",
        "Shipping on day three replaces this plan with a different procedure, one that\n",
        "checks the p-value every day and acts the first time it falls below 0.05. The\n",
        "day-twenty rule rejects when $p_{20} \\leq 0.05$; the daily rule rejects when\n",
        "$\\min_{t \\leq 20} p_t \\leq 0.05$. These events need not have the same null\n",
        "probability.\n",
        "\n",
        "If the twenty daily analyses were independent, at least one of them would\n",
        "fall below 0.05 in a null experiment with probability\n",
        "$1 - (1 - 0.05)^{20} \\approx 0.64$. The cumulative analyses are correlated\n",
        "because each one reuses the data from earlier days, so 64% is only an\n",
        "independence benchmark. The simulation below estimates the false-positive\n",
        "rate for these correlated analyses. The 5% guarantee applies to the\n",
        "prespecified day-twenty analysis, not to the rule that rejects after the first\n",
        "daily p-value at or below 0.05.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout}\n",
        "Opening the experiment's interim-results dashboard each day does not change\n",
        "the pointwise calibration of that day's p-value. The pointwise 5% guarantee\n",
        "does not cover a decision rule that uses an interim threshold crossing to\n",
        "stop, ship, roll back, or extend the experiment.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "**Anytime-valid inference** calibrates inference for repeated looks at\n",
        "accumulating data when any review may trigger a decision.\n",
        "\n",
        "## What SAVI changes\n",
        "\n",
        "Safe anytime-valid inference (SAVI) replaces the ordinary p-value and\n",
        "confidence interval with sequential counterparts calibrated for repeated\n",
        "monitoring. In the large randomized experiments considered here, a 5% SAVI\n",
        "test satisfies, under the method's assumptions, an asymptotic bound of 5% on\n",
        "the probability that the sequential p-value is at or below 0.05 at any review.\n",
        "The review schedule therefore need not be chosen before launch. A\n",
        "prespecified rule that rejects the zero-effect null the first time the SAVI\n",
        "p-value is at or below 0.05 has asymptotic type-I error of at most 5%. The\n",
        "sequential p-value has an interval companion, the **confidence sequence**: a\n",
        "sequence of intervals that contains the true effect at every review\n",
        "simultaneously, with asymptotic probability of at least 95%.\n",
        "\n",
        "At the sample sizes used here, the SAVI confidence sequences are wider than\n",
        "ordinary confidence intervals, and the sequential p-values are typically\n",
        "larger. The SAVI statistics are calibrated across all possible stopping points\n",
        "rather than one prespecified date. A lift well above the planning value can\n",
        "still cross the 0.05 threshold before day twenty, while a lift near or below\n",
        "that value typically takes longer to detect than under the fixed-horizon test.\n",
        "\n",
        "The first two simulations use sequential p-values to measure false positives\n",
        "under daily stopping and relate effect size to stopping time. The next three\n",
        "use confidence sequences to certify a Java-to-Kotlin rewrite, report weekly\n",
        "holdout results, and make hourly rollback decisions for a canary release. A\n",
        "final simulation studies regression adjustment. The `PyFixest` API and the\n",
        "method's assumptions follow.\n",
        "\n",
        "All simulations use `PyFixest`'s implementation of the linear-model method of\n",
        "[Lindon et al. (2026)](https://doi.org/10.1080/01621459.2026.2692052), which\n",
        "combines anytime-valid inference with regression adjustment for variance\n",
        "reduction.^[Its closed-form formulas also make the method fast to compute.]"
      ],
